<TITLE> Argentina, Brazil suspend WTO dispute over resin </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 GENEVA, Feb 7 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Argentina and Brazil have suspended a dispute at the World Trade Organisation (WTO) as the two governments work out a solution to their row over imports of Argentine resins into Brazil, diplomats said on Thursday. The WTO set up a panel in July last year to investigate Argentina's complaint that anti-dumping duties applied by Brazil to PET resins from Argentina violated world trade rules. PET resins are used to make plastic bottles and other consumer goods containers. Brasilia and Buenos Aires are working on a long-term solution to the dispute, Adrian Serra, an official at Argentina's WTO mission, told Reuters. "As part of that long-term solution Brazil suspended the application of the measure for one year for the PET resins coming into the Brazilian market from Argentina, and Argentina decided to follow suit with the dispute settlement at the WTO," Serra said. A Brazilian diplomat said the case had been effectively dropped. The WTO said that Argentina had requested the suspension of the dispute after Brazil had decided to suspend the anti-dumping duties on imports of PET resin from Argentina. The case arose from a complaint by M&G Fibras & Resinas Ltda, a Brazilian unit of Italian family-owned Gruppo Mossi & Ghisolfi (M&G Group), a chemical engineering group that is the world's biggest producer of PET for packagi
